The pistol was developed in the late 1950s at the Institute for Artillery Research (Polish: Zak‚ad Broni Strzeleckiej Centralnego Badawczego Poligonu Artyleryjskiego, which later became the Military Institute of Armament Technology, Polish: Wojskowy Instytut Techniczny Uzbrojenia w Zielonce-WITU) by a team consisting of: W. Czepukajtis, R. Zimny, H. Adamczyk, M. Adamczyk, S. Kaczmarski and J. Pyzel. The P-64 is also known as the CZAK[1] (an acronym of the designers' last names with the exception of J. Pyzel, who joined the team after the name had been established). title: For Sale/Trade:  1916 Spanish Mauser (7.62x51)
postcontent: I am offering a 1916 Spanish Mauser chambered in 7.62 NATO (7.62x51). The overall condition of this rifle is very good/excellent . With the exception of the safety lever, all serial numbers match. The condition of the bore is excellent, essentially perfect to my eyes. The previous owner of this rifle skillfully repaired a cracked wrist as well as reblued the firearm, and frankly his work was outstanding. All and all, this is both a cosmetically beautiful and functionally perfect firearm. I got this rifle lumped into a larger trade, and I already have a couple M1916s, so I am selling this one. Leather sling is included. Don't hesitate to request higher quality pictures or ask questions. I have personally detail stripped this firearm, and I can say with full confidence that it has nothing to hide.A word about Spanish M1916 Mausers:If you are knowledgable about 1916 Mauser's, you will be pleased to learn that this particular rifle was originally purchased from SAMCO in the 1990's. This rifle is NOT one of the bottom of the barrel rejects which recently flooded the market after SAMCO's liquidation sale. Additionally, the previous owner was a knowledgable man and fired low pressure handloads through this rifle, so it was not abused by full power .308 in the way that others like it have been.If you are not familiar with the M1916 rifle, you should be aware that there is great debate on the history, safety, and proper chambering of these rifles. I won't turn this classified ad into a history lesson, but here is the main takeaway: This is a European military rifle chambered for a European military cartridge (7.62 NATO). This rifle is NOT chambered for the American hunting cartridge .308 Winchester. While these two rounds are often considered interchangable in a modern context (and a great many rifles can safely fire both), they are in fact dimensionally different and have inconsisent pressure ratings. In the case of this particular rifle, the consensus is that these slight differences are significant enough, and the rifle antiquated enough, that .308 Winchester is potentially UNSAFE to fire. While a great many folks have fired large amounts of .308 out of these rifles without any recorded consequence, the potential for harm exists, and therefor it is strongly advised that your only use the NATO spec ammunition that the gun was designed to fire (or better still, handloads). Additionally, this rifle is not chambered for 7.62 CETME, as some "internet experts" will claim.The bottom line is that the M1916 mauser is a historic military firearm which operates on a 125 year old action. Unlike for example, new production hunting rifles, it wasn't designed to to be idiot proof. So long however as you respect the capabilities and limitations of a small ring Mauser, it is a highly capable and versatile tool. You can, in perfect safety, load this gun to serve you as a full power deer rifle, a rock solid truck gun, a respectable target rifle, or a knockabout plinker.
